<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much does it cost to charge an electric car at home?", answer: "Home charging cost depends on your electricity rate and battery size. At the US average of $0.13 per kWh, charging a 75 kWh battery from 10% to 80% costs about $6.33 to $9.75 depending on charger efficiency. Monthly costs for a typical 40-mile daily commute are $40-$60. This is roughly 3-4 times cheaper than gasoline for the same distance." },
  { question: "What is charger efficiency and why does it matter?", answer: "Charger efficiency is the percentage of electricity from the grid that actually reaches the battery. Level 2 chargers are about 85-90% efficient, meaning 10-15% of electricity is lost as heat during charging. Level 1 chargers can be less efficient at 80-85%. DC fast chargers are typically 90-95% efficient. This lost energy still appears on your electric bill, increasing the true cost of charging." },
  { question: "Is it cheaper to charge at home or at a public charger?", answer: "Home charging is almost always cheaper. Home electricity costs $0.10-$0.20 per kWh in most areas. Public Level 2 chargers cost $0.15-$0.30 per kWh. DC fast chargers cost $0.30-$0.60 per kWh, sometimes with session fees on top. Some EV manufacturers offer free Supercharging promotions, and many workplaces provide free Level 2 charging." },
  { question: "How long does it take to charge an EV at different levels?", answer: "Level 1 (standard 120V outlet, 1.4 kW) adds about 3-5 miles per hour, taking 40-60 hours for a full charge. Level 2 (240V, 7-11 kW) adds 20-30 miles per hour, completing a full charge in 6-12 hours. DC Fast Charging (50-350 kW) can add 100-200 miles in 20-40 minutes. Tesla Superchargers (up to 250 kW) charge from 10-80% in about 25-35 minutes." },
  { question: "What does cost per mile mean for an EV?", answer: "Cost per mile is the fuel cost for every mile driven. For EVs, it is calculated by dividing the charging cost by the miles of range added. A typical EV costs $0.03-$0.05 per mile when charged at home, compared to $0.10-$0.15 per mile for a gasoline vehicle. This 60-70% fuel savings is one of the biggest financial advantages of electric vehicles." }
]) %>

